It can be appropriate to acknowledge it. ("Wait a minute, how come you're speaking English?" "Maybe some kind of quantum affinity between our timelines made it more likely that we would be linked to one with the same dominant spoken language." "Really?" "I dno, lol") Spending chapter after chapter on the viewpoint character's struggle with the language is filler. I want to see the protagonist talking to the qt anthro girl, not lecture the viewer for ten chapters about agglutinative languages. If I really like the characters I may try to skip forward and find a point where they can actually communicate and it's an actual story instead of a textbook on comparative linguistics.

World Building Question.

So my setting, wolf anthros (one species out of several), and I'm having a question of identity.

In one part of the world, wolf anthros are a majority species in their own nation called Wulvland (named after them). The Wulvish have their own culture, language and national identity based on the picts. They share their country with a human minority, and their nation is in a union with a human majority nation called Wesenland with its own culture etc, similar to how England and Scotland are formed to form the state of the UK (except in this case, hmofa was used to form the two kingdoms in an union through marriage).

Meanwhile, other wolf anthros exist across the world which haven't formed their own nations. They are instead akin to nobility, historically acting as warriors of a nation, with wolf anthro packs/families being like noble families. Their national identity is their primary identity, with pack values and traditions being a different identity.

How confusing does this sound? Because I'm not sure if this is too much for a reader to handle, especially where this isn't the focus of the story. But I hate when a whole race/species is characterised as one hegemonic group.

The point the other Anon made is that if they're the aristocracy, it's by default their own nation even if they're a minority population. That's kind of how being a ruling class works, especially if it's supposed to be a feudal society where the nobility also forms the military backbone. If you want them to be the bulk of the warrior class (or, at least, the professional warrior class) but not nobility, they would have to be more culturally akin to empires that recruited fighting forces from warrior cultures that were essentially foreign, or so far from politics to not have a bone in them. Some of the more famous examples, such as the Varangians, were small, specialist bodyguard units. But that kind of makes sense if they're a minority population. No feudal army would draw exclusively from the nobility, after all, and would demand military service from its citizens. In short, if this is a feudal society, those human farmers would pick up arms during war and return home for the planting season just as they did in real life. The formation of the professional Roman army was a response to Rome expanding too much for its citizen soldiers to be able to return to their farms every year.

Basically, what you're suggesting sounds like you want them to be military professionals, not rulers. But you're coining it in terms of rulership, hence the confusion.

Anonymous Fri 26 May 2023 15:12:25 No.56802191 Report

>>56801720
Kinda. I know about the Varangians as well as groups like the Ottoman janissaries and the Swiss guard. But while I imagine that used to exist in the world I've created, it's kind of what I'm trying to talk about.

The overall issue I'm trying to address in world-building is how different species evolved in different environments and how that shapes their historic social interactions. How does a species evolve to interact with humans from one society to another. Not many stories explore this.

Many stories in the masterbin tend to be the following:
>seperate human state and anthro state
>human and anthro cohabitation in a single state which is barely addressed beyond minor details and descriptions.
>Human and anthro separation in a single state which is often done with little thought on the implications.
>Human dominated or anthro dominated state with possible segregation/oppression of one or the other.

Many of these have ALL anthros in one catagory, and ALL humans in the other. There's no examining how certain anthros would interact to humans AND other anthros.

What I'm trying to explore is how different species fit into different society, and how they evolved into that over time.

In this case, the Wulver nation is mostly anthro wolves because the environment suits their physical predisposition. Wulvers are in all classes, and take up all professions as they're the majority. Humans exist, but as a minority.

However, in some nations anthro wolves evolved to become a specialised warrior class/nobility because of their fighting prowess. They earned this status, and kept it through their ability to fight.

I also don't know why I'm thinking about all this. The story is set in a mid 20th century technological setting where the nobility is a rotting corpse of what it once was and most 'warrior culture' is tradition and nothing more.

I'm also very tired and probably not wording this all correctly.
